article.headline: Indiana unbeaten since Artest's return
article.linkText: Artest key on both ends in Pacers' OT win
article.story:
INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- Ron Artest came back from thumb surgery much quicker than expected, and the Indiana Pacers sure are glad he did. Artest led the Pacers with 23 points and shut down Vince Carter for the last 17 minutes to lead the Pacers to a 94-84 overtime win over the Toronto Raptors on Tuesday night. "Every night he's found a way to get involved, even with his hand the way it is," said Jermaine O'Neal, who had 20 points and 18 rebounds. "Every possession, he's making an impact for us." The Pacers scored the first eight points in overtime en route to their sixth win in a row. Jamaal Tinsley opened the extra period with a 3-pointer, O'Neal hit a jumper and Reggie Miller added a deep 3-pointer as the shot clock was winding down to give Indiana an 89-81 lead. "We had our chances at the end of regulation," Toronto coach Kevin O'Neill said. "They took over in overtime and played very well." Indiana never would have had that chance if not for Artest's huge contributions on both ends of the floor. His aggressiveness on offense helped put the Pacers in the bonus in the fourth and allowed them to chip away at Toronto's lead, and his defensive performance against one of the most offensively talented players in the NBA was even more impressive. Artest limited Carter to just one point and six shots in the fourth quarter and overtime, most of which were contested. "In the fourth, Ronnie really turned up the defense, made it hard for him to breathe out there," Pacers coach Rick Carlisle said. "That was the key." Not bad for a guy who had surgery to repair torn ligaments in his left thumb Feb. 19, leading many to believe the Pacers would have to play without him until the playoffs. "It wasn't me saying that, it was a lot of other people saying that," Artest said. "I knew I was going to come back pretty fast." He returned just 12 days later, and the Pacers have won every game since. That streak seemed destined to end early in the fourth quarter. Donyell Marshall opened the quarter with all 10 points of a 10-2 Toronto run. His 3-pointer gave the Raptors a 73-66 lead with 9:34 to play, but the Raptors couldn't find enough offense to keep up with the NBA-leading Pacers (48-16). "We did everything we could to stay in the game," said Toronto's Chris Bosh, who had 19 points and eight rebounds. "They just hit a lot of big shots to put us away." Carter led Toronto with 28 points, but managed just one point after the third quarter. He missed two chances to put the Raptors ahead in the final 30 seconds of regulation, including a wide open look with eight seconds left. "It's a shot I should have made, plain and simple," Carter said. "I make that, we go home." Carter wasted no time getting going, scoring 15 points on 7-of-11 shooting in the first quarter. Toronto shot 59.5 percent in the first half to take a 50-46 halftime lead. He tormented Artest, one of the best perimeter defenders in the league, with 21 points in the first half, but Artest got the better of him when it counted. "He came out on fire," Artest said. "I got more help from the team instead of trying to do it by myself." O'Neal, who was 7-for-24 from the field, scored seven points during an 11-0 fourth quarter run that gave the Pacers a 79-75 lead with 3:24 to play. Bosh answered the Pacers' big run with two free throws and a layup to tie the game at 79, and the teams traded baskets before going into overtime tied at 81. Marshall had 13 points and 13 rebounds and recently signed Rod Strickland had 14 points, 16 assists and seven rebounds for Toronto. Jamaal Tinsley had 12 points and 11 assists for Indiana.

Game notes
O'Neill served as an assistant during Carlisle's two-year tenure in Detroit. ... Kareem Abdul-Jabbar, recently hired by New York Knicks GM Isiah Thomas, was in town scouting the game. ... Tinsley returned to the lineup after missing one game with a sprained toe on his right foot. ... O'Neal picked up a technical foul at 6:42 of the second quarter for arguing an offensive foul call.
